Be cautious about adding too many ingredients; combining more than three core components (protein, vegetable, grain) can often lead to 'overcomplicated' items with zero or negative value. If you reach a value of 80, it's generally safer to submit rather than risk overcomplicating the dish. Also, pay close attention to any specific tips provided, as they can lead to highly valuable items.

message: Hello future crafter! Here's what I learned: 1. Prioritize cooking: Almost all raw ingredients (proteins like fish/bacon/beans, vegetables like carrot/tomato/potato/green beans) benefit from being cooked with the 游댠 stove first. This often raises their value to 20. 2. Soak, then cook rice: If you have 游 rice, use 游눦 water to soak it, then cook the soaked rice with the 游댠 stove. This seems to be a key step for rice. 3. Optimal Combinations (The 'Golden Trio'): The highest scores (60-100) consistently come from combining one cooked protein, one cooked grain, and one cooked vegetable. Look for a cooked item, combine it with another cooked item, then add a third cooked item to reach max value. 4. Avoid overcomplicating: Once you have a high-value item with three components, STOP. Adding a fourth component almost always drops the item's value to 0 or even negative. This is the most crucial rule to remember. 5. Use specific tips first: If a player before you left specific instructions (like 'cook beans, don't soak'), follow those first, then apply these general rules.

Generally, soak grains (like wheat, rice, corn, bread) in water first, then cook them on the stove. Cook proteins and other vegetables separately on the stove. A common high-value recipe involves combining cooked protein with cooked soaked grain (often yields 60 points), and then adding a cooked vegetable to this dish can bring it to 100 points (e.g., cooked beet or broccoli to a cooked bean & soaked grain dish). Be very cautious when combining multiple complex dishes or adding too many ingredients; this often leads to a sharp decrease in value, even from a high score. Focus on the core 2-3 ingredient combinations that reach high values. Tools like water and stove are single-use.

message: Focus on cooking individual raw proteins and vegetables with the stove first to get value (0 to 20). Then, combine 2-3 *cooked* items to create high-value dishes (e.g., cooked protein + cooked vegetable). Sometimes adding one raw vegetable to a cooked combo works well, but be very careful with adding a fourth ingredient, as this frequently leads to 'overcomplicated' items with negative values. Avoid re-cooking an already cooked combined item with the stove if it has 'cooked' features on all components, as it can lead to 'overcooked' and drastically reduce value. Using water on 'overcooked' or 'overcomplicated' items generally makes them worse.
